Seattle Parking Demand Prediction

Zixuan Xu & Jia Yuan

December 12, 2019

1 - Introduction

The purpose of the model is to predict the parking demand in Seattle. Currently, the zoning regulations have a very arbitrary way to set the numbers of parking spaces for different developments. The zoning doesnât take the existing supply of parking into account and only consider the singular land use type of a development. The regulations on parking spots are also static in a way that it doesnât change according to the new developments coming into the area. Furthermore, our targeted city, Seattle, has been one of the pioneers in the United States to use pricing as a tool to manage parking demand, which the parking regulations are not taken that into account either. Therefore, the current zoning regulations on parking are limited in terms of its inability to accurately aligning supply with the constantly-changing demand in a dynamic manner.

Our model has incorporated multiple variables that can reflect the dynamic nature of the parking demand in Seattle. Since the City of Seattle has set different pricing for parking spaces based on the days of a week and the time of a day, some of the key independent variables include parking pricing, parking time period, and parking occupancy from Seattleâs Annual Parking Study.

Dynamic parking pricing and performance-based parking have continuously been a hot topic both nationally and internationally. Building a parking prediction model based on the dynamic principal can not only help the City improve their parking regulations and optimize parking supply, but also offer some examples and insights for the further implementation of such a parking management concept.

The city government can incorporate the tool powered by the model on their zoning website for developers to explore parking needs and propose projects accordingly. The model also serves users beyond governmental agencies and developers. The general public can also utilize this tool as a way to see a new developmentâs impact on parking demands.

2 - Data

For this project, we collected data from the following sources: - Blockface data and the annual parking study data from Seattle Open Data Portal - Amenity data from Open Street Map
- American Census Survey 5-year estimates, 2017

2.1 - Data Wrangling and Feature Engineering

The primary data sets we have used include the blockface data and the annual parking study data from Seattle Open Data Portal. These two data sets include the historical parking observations at blockface level and the geospatial location of each blockface.

2.1.1 - Independent Variables

Firstly, we created independent variables for the model through data wrangling and feature engineering.
The sptial independent variables include: - Number of restaurants within the 1320 feet buffer of a blockface
- Number of shops within the 1320 feet buffer of a blockface
- Average distance to the nearest 5 bus stop of a blockface
- Distance to the nearest university of a blockface
- Distance to the nearest hospital of a blockface
- Distance to the nearest community center of a blockface
- Distance to the nearest pharmacy of a blockface
- Seattle neighborhood of a blockface
- Population density of a blockface based on its block group, 2017 ACS 5-year estimates
- Percentage of population driving to work of a blockface based on its block group, 2017 ACS 5-year estimates
- Percentage of family without vehicle of a blockface based on its block group, 2017 ACS 5-year estimates
- Percentage of family with 1 vehicle of a blockface based on its block group, 2017 ACS 5-year estimates
- Percentage of family with 2 or more vehicles of a blockface based on its block group, 2017 ACS 5-year estimates
- Zoning code of a blockface
- Land use type of a blockface - Road type of a blockface
- Surface width of a blockface - Oneway designation of a blockface
- Slope percentage of a blockface
- Spatial lag - Time lag

2.1.1.6 - Internal Characteristics

To obtain internal characteristics related to each parking observation, we created some independent variables.
For example, we noticed that there were some blockfaces during certain time have zero parking spaces while positive total vehicle counts, which indicates that the parking spaces are unavailable during that time, and all the cars are illegally parked. Therefore, we created a column called “noparking” to represent the availability of parking spaces during a certain time period for a blockface and then manually filled the zero parking spaces in the data set as the actual number of parking spaces when it was allowed to park, in case we cannot calculate the parking occupancy with a zero denominator.
Meanwhile, we created a column called “timeperiod” with four time periods during a day, including morning (7am to 10am), afternoon (11am to 5pm), evening (6pm to 9pm), and night (10pm to 6am). It’s known that, even for the same place, the parking demand can fluctuate greatly within a day. Therefore, the “timepriod” column will try to capture the trend of parking occupancy rate during different time periods.
Moreover, as parking demand may also vary for weekday and weekend, we created a column called “ifWeekday” to indicate if a parking observation was recorded on weekdays or not.

detach(package:papeR)
#create noparking in parking data
parking <- annualparking%>%
  mutate(noparking = ifelse(annualparking$parking_spaces == 0, 1, 0))

#change the unofficial parking spaces to regular parking spaces
parking_max <- parking%>%
  group_by(elmntkey)%>%
  summarise(maxparking = max(parking_spaces))

parking <- parking %>%
  left_join(parking_max)

#break out the time stamp
parking <- parking%>%
  mutate(interval60 = floor_date(mdy_hm(date_time), unit = "hour"),
         hour = hour(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE),
         date = date(interval60))
#create four time periods
parking <- parking%>%
  mutate(timeperiod = ifelse(hour > 7 & hour < 11, "morning", 
                             ifelse(hour > 10 & hour < 18, "afternoon",
                                    ifelse(hour > 17 & hour < 22, "evening", "night"))),
         #create weekday/weekend indicator
         ifWeekday = ifelse(isWeekday(date),1,0),
         #calculate parking occupancy
         occupancy = as.numeric(total_vehicle_count)/as.numeric(maxparking))

2.1.2 - Dependent Variable

To represent the parking demand of each blockface, we calculated the occupancy rate for each parking observation as the dependent variable of our prediction model.

detach(package:papeR)
#calculate average parking occupancy by time period
parking_ocu <- parking%>%
  group_by(elmntkey,
           timeperiod,
           ifWeekday)%>%
  summarise(occupancy = mean(as.numeric(total_vehicle_count)/as.numeric(maxparking)))%>%
  ungroup()

#join parking data to blockface
parking1 <- parking %>%
  left_join(blocks_joined4%>%
              mutate(ELMNTKEY=as.character(ELMNTKEY)),by=c('elmntkey'='ELMNTKEY'))

#join above features to parking data
parking2 <- parking1 %>%
  left_join(blockface_pt %>%
              st_set_geometry(NULL)%>%
              select(shop_nn1, restaurant_nn1,busStop_nn5,university_nn1,hospital_nn1,pharmacy_nn1,communityCenter_nn1,ELMNTKEY)%>%
              mutate(ELMNTKEY = as.character(ELMNTKEY)), by=c('elmntkey'='ELMNTKEY'))

2.1.3 - Spatial Lag

For any spatial regression model, spatial lag is always a strong predictor. Here we created a spatial lag for each blockface, showing the average occupancy rate of its nearest 5 neighbors during the same time period.

#create subset of different time periods
parking3 <- parking2 %>%
  as.data.frame()%>%
  st_as_sf(sf_column_name = "geometry")%>%
  st_transform(crs=4326)%>%
  st_make_valid()%>%
  filter(is.finite(occupancy))

parking3 <- parking3[!st_is_empty(parking3),,drop=FALSE]
#weekday
nb_day_morning <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'morning'&parking3$ifWeekday == 1),]
nb_day_afternoon <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'afternoon'&parking3$ifWeekday == 1),]
nb_day_evening <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'evening'&parking3$ifWeekday == 1),]
nb_day_night <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'night'&parking3$ifWeekday == 1),]
#weekend
nb_end_morning <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'morning'&parking3$ifWeekday == 0),]
nb_end_afternoon <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'afternoon'&parking3$ifWeekday == 0),]
nb_end_evening <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'evening'&parking3$ifWeekday == 0),]
nb_end_night <- parking3[which(parking3$timeperiod == 'night'&parking3$ifWeekday == 0),]

#get midpoints for linestrings
coords1 <- st_coordinates(st_centroid(nb_day_morning)) 
coords2 <- st_coordinates(st_centroid(nb_day_afternoon))%>%
  na.omit()

coords8 <- st_coordinates(st_centroid(nb_end_night))%>%

# average occupancy rate of nearest 5 neighbors for different time periods
neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords1, k=5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_day_morning$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_day_morning$occupancy)

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords2, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_day_afternoon$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_day_afternoon$occupancy)

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords3, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_day_evening$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_day_evening$occupancy)

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords4, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_day_night$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_day_night$occupancy)

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords5, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_end_morning$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_end_morning$occupancy)

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords6, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_end_afternoon$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_end_afternoon$occupancy)

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords7, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_end_evening$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_end_evening$occupancy)

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords8, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
nb_end_night$SpatialLag_5NB <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, nb_end_night$occupancy)

#Combine subsets
parking3 <- rbind(nb_day_morning,nb_day_afternoon,nb_day_evening,nb_day_night,
                  nb_end_afternoon,nb_end_evening,nb_end_morning,nb_end_night)

2.1.4 - Time Lag

Since our annual parking study dataset has timestamp for each observation, we created a time lag to capture the trend of parking demand as time changes.

parking.panel <- 
  parking3 %>% 
  arrange(elmntkey, interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(occupancy,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(occupancy,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(occupancy,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(occupancy,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(occupancy,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lag(occupancy,24))

         pct_5more = as.numeric(pct_5more),
         timeperiod = as.factor(timeperiod),
         ifWeekday = as.factor(ifWeekday)) %>%
  #create percentage of family with two or more vehicles
  mutate(pct_2vehmore = pct_2veh+pct_3veh+pct_4veh+pct_5more)%>%
  #select needed columns
  select(elmntkey,occupancy,SIDE,shop_nn1,restaurant_nn1,busStop_nn5,nhood,pop_dens,pct_drive,pct_noveh,pct_1veh,pct_2vehmore,
         timeperiod,ifWeekday,zoning,category_d,university_nn1,hospital_nn1,pharmacy_nn1,communityCenter_nn1,lagHour,lag2Hours,lag4Hours,
         lag12Hours,lag1day,
         SPEEDLIMIT,ONEWAY,ARTDESCRIPT,SURFACEWIDTH,SLOPE_PCT,SpatialLag_5NB,
         geometry)%>%
  rename(landuse = category_d)%>%
  na.omit()%>%
  filter(is.finite(occupancy))%>%
  filter(occupancy >= 0)

As parking demand is significantly influenced by time segment, time lag becomes extraordinarily important in our model. From the scatterplots, we can conclude that all the time lags are significantly related to the parking occupancy rate. The only difference is how much they relates to each other. The time lag of one hour has the strongest correlation with parking demand, indicating that it is highly possible that lagHour can become a robust predictor in the regression model. Compared to other time lags, lag1day has the weakiest correlation with parking occupancy rate, which is acceptable because it is part of time lag’s nature.

4 - Methods

4.1 Space-time Process

For this project, we used linear regression model to predict the occupancy rate for a parking space during a certain time period. As parking demand fluctuates during a day, one day is split into four periods: morning (7am - 10am), afternoon (11am - 5pm), evening (6pm - 9pm), and night (10pm - 6am). Meanwhile, days are also split into weekdays and weekends. The two indicators are the primary predictors representing time elements.Combined with the geospatial location and other spatial structure (such as distance to the nearest bus stop) related to each parking space, the space-time process of our model captured the typical space-time patterns for any parking behavior.
Moreover, to capture the spatial-temporal trend of parking demand, we created spatial lag (5 nearest neighbors) and time lag (2 hours, 4 hours, 12 housrs, and 24 hours) as independent predictors for the model.
## 4.2 - Models
### 4.2.1 - Training/Test Set
First, to test the accuracy of our model, we split the data set into train set (70%) and test set (30%).Meanwhile, make sure that we have included those categorical variables (neighborhoods, landuse, zoning, timeperiod, and ifWeekday) in both train set and test set.

# Create a 70% train set

  p = 0.70, list = FALSE)
train_set <- parking_final[inTrain,] 
test_set <- parking_final[-inTrain,]

For the little difference of R-sqaured between the experiment model and the initial model, it makes more sense to delete those amenity features from the initial model and keep the prediction model more clear. Although some predictors in the model show high p-values, indicating a low statistically significance level, we decided to keep those variables because they have relatively high coefficient estimates. Thus, the experiment model is our final regression model.
From the model summary, the most important factor for the prediction model is, with no doubt, the one hour lag of parking occupancy rate. Such a finding exemplifies the fact that parking occupancy rate is sensitive to time. On the other hand, the statistical significance of spatial lag, land use type, zoning, and neighborhood indicators verifies the spatial pattern of parking demand exists in Seattle.
Generally speaking, our method of space-time process successfully captures the characteristics and trends of parking demand in Seattle.

5 - Results

5.1 - Test Set Prediction

As we already built up the model, we can test the prediction accuracy of model on the test set by calculating the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and Mean Absolute Percent Error (MAPE). Also, the Absolute Error histogram can help us understand the accuracy better.

test_set <-
  test_set %>%
  mutate(occupancyPredict = predict(reg2, test_set),
         occupancyError = occupancy - occupancyPredict,
         occupancyAbsError = abs(occupancy - occupancyPredict),
         occupancyAPE = (abs(occupancy - occupancyPredict)) / occupancy)%>%
  filter(is.finite(occupancyAPE))

MAE.test <-  mean(test_set$occupancyAbsError, na.rm = TRUE)

MAPE.test <- mean(test_set$occupancyAPE * 100, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
  round(2) %>%
  paste("%")

error_sum = data_frame('R-squared' = summary(reg2)$r.squared,
                       'Adjusted R-squared' = summary(reg2)$adj.r.squared,
                       'MAE' = MAE.test,'MAPE'=MAPE.test)
kable(error_sum,align="c",caption = "Table 5.1, Model Error Summary - Test Set") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"))%>%
  row_spec(0,bold = T, color = "white", background = "#CD5C5C")

5.3 - 100-Fold Cross Validation

To test the general accuracy level and generalizability of our prediction model, we used k-fold cross-validation. K-fold cross-validation is a commonly used cross validation method for linear regression model.

detach(package:papeR)
# specify the number of k-fold partitions
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100)

# begin the validation
set.seed(825)

reg2.cv <- train(occupancy ~ ., data = (train_set%>%
                                    st_set_geometry(NULL))%>%
                   dplyr::select(occupancy,nhood,pop_dens,pct_drive,

                           SPEEDLIMIT,ONEWAY,SURFACEWIDTH,
                           SLOPE_PCT,SIDE,SpatialLag_5NB,lagHour,lag4Hours,lag12Hours,lag1day,
                           ARTDESCRIPT), 
                 method = "lm", trControl = fitControl, na.action = na.pass)


# mean MAE
mean(reg2.cv$resample[,3])

# standard deviation of MAE
sd(reg2.cv$resample[,3])
# plot the MAE histogram
ggplot(as.data.frame(reg2.cv$resample), aes(MAE)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 50, colour="white", fill = "#CD5C5C") +

After running the 100-fold crass validation, the result of each fold is normally distributed, as shown in the MAE histogram. Although the distribution of MAE is not perfectly normal, most of the folds have an MAE between 0.16 and 0.17, which is an acceptable variance range for a 100-fold cross-validation. In other words, our prediction model performs similarly across different data sets, in terms of prediction errors.

6 - Generalizability

Although the k-fold cross-validation above demonstrated the overall generalizability level of our model for different sets of data, we still do not know whether the model does a good job in predicting across all neighborhoods and during all timeperiods. We choose to verify generalizability from the perspectives of neighborhoos and time periods because our regression model shows the spatial-temporal trend of parking demand across Seattle. A good prediction model shall be able to predict similarly, in terms of prediction error, for any spatial location or time period.

7 - Conclusion

Although the model only has an MAPE of 29% on the test set, we can tell from the model summary statistics that it successfully demonstrated the spatial-temporal trends of parking occupancy rate in Seattle. The spatial lag and one hour time lag are the two most important predictors in the linear regression model, from the perspectives of space and time. In terms of generalizability, the model predicts equally for neighborhoods that existed in the annual parking data, which is the downtown and relatively urbanized areas in Seattle, such as Capitol Hill, University District, and Central Area. Therefore, we recommend that our model be used in downtown Seattle. Meanwhile, the model can predict equally for afternoon, evening, and night (11am to 6am (+1)), but performs relatively poorly while predicting parking occupancy rate in the morning.

7.1 - Use Case Analysis

Our use case is to build an application to advise developers how much parking spaces shall be put into a property development project based on property type, surrounding characteristics, land use types, and so on. Moreover, the parking demand advice is dynamically adjusted, with parking demand fluctuating accordingly when it comes to different time periods (morning, afternoon, evening, and night). Such an application can not only add more interactive and dynamic features into the current parking requirement in the zoning code but also help developers capture the dynamic nature of parking demand and better allocate the limited development resources.
Currently, the regression model we built has successfully integrated the landuse and zoning codes of Seattle, which can become the input information offered by the users, to help predict parking demand. Also, time periods and day of weeks are incorporated into the model, assisting developers predict a dynamic parking demand. The time lag and spatial lag will be added into the primary data set continuously, offering real-time predictors for the model. In this way, even when the model gets older, it can still collect the latest parking occupancy rate and convert it into a parking demand prediction for a new project.
In conclusion, our model fits the requirements of our anticipated use case.

7.2 - Potential Improving Direction

Limited by the processing size and amount of time, our model is still defected and can be improved from the following perspectives.
* Firstly, the primary data set we used is the annual parking study data provided by Seattle Open Data Portal, which is already handled and trimmed to requirements. In the very begining of this project, we found an up-to-date parking dataset on the Portal. This data set is updated regularly, with new parking observations constantly added in. Compared to our annual study data, such an up-to-date dataset can enhance the dynamic nature and increase the reliabilty of our regression model when we need to predict the parking demand generated by an apartment development project. However, since the dataset is huge (more than 176 million rows) and we have limited amount of processing power, we finally decided to stick to the annual parking data. For those organizations with sufficient processing power and urgent need for parking demand prediction, the up-to-date parking data is a good point to start with.
* Secondly, independent variables more than the ones we have used should be investigated so that the accuracy and generalizability of the model can be further improved. Besides more accurate and up-to-date parking data, demographics data, business activity data and other kinds of data might also influence the parking demand in Seattle. Furthermore, given the unique weather that Seattle has, it would be interesting to look into the correlation between weather and the parking demand.
